\description{
Generate synthetic genotype data for one or more populations, each treated
as a nuclear family with a known mother and multiple offspring. Paternal
contribution can be unknown (mixture per marker) or known (single sire).
Optionally, input a pedigree to form families; otherwise families are
created as independent populations. This function orchestrates per-population
simulation by calling an internal single-population core.
}
\details{
\strong{Markers and recombination}
\itemize{
\item The union of markers has length \code{T_markers = T}. If a pedigree is not
provided, each population is assigned a subset of these markers according
to \code{marker_intersection}. Shared markers retain the same order across
populations; non-shared markers are scattered (not blocky).
\item The recombination vector \code{r_true} is common to all populations, either
supplied via \code{r_vec} (length \code{T-1}) or filled as a constant \code{r_const}.
}

\strong{Maternal genotypes}

Controlled by \code{maternal_geno_mode}:
\itemize{
\item \code{"HWE"} (default): for markers present in a population, simulate maternal
genotype under HWE at allele-A frequency \code{maternal_pA} (scalar or vector
of length \code{T}). Absent markers remain \code{NA}.
\item \code{"all_het"}: force all present maternal markers to be heterozygous (Aa).
\item \code{"vector"}: use the provided integer vector \code{maternal_M_given} (0/1/2/NA),
aligned to the union marker set. Absent markers in a population are kept
as \code{NA} regardless of values in \code{maternal_M_given}.
}

\strong{Paternal composition per marker}
\itemize{
\item If a population has an \emph{unknown sire}, the paternal genotype mixture at
present markers follows HWE with allele-A frequency
\code{paternal_pA_base} (scalar or length-T vector). To induce population
heterogeneity, a zero-mean Gaussian jitter with SD \code{paternal_pA_sd} is
added \strong{per marker} and truncated into \verb{(1e-4, 1-1e-4)}.
\item If a population has a \emph{known sire} (probability
\code{known_sire_prob_per_pop} when no pedigree is given), the sire genotype is
drawn \strong{per marker} under HWE at the population's perturbed allele frequency
and encoded as a one-hot column in the 3 x T \code{pi_true} matrix for that
population. This is a \strong{simulation-only} device that fixes a paternal
\emph{genotype} composition; the paternal genotypes are generated \strong{independently
across markers} (there is no linked paternal meiosis and no paternal
haplotype). It does \strong{not} correspond to, and must not be read as, support for
known-sire / full-sib linkage mapping: the estimation functions in this package
model the open-pollinated / unknown-sire case only (the paternal contribution is
integrated out per marker through a dam-specific gametic frequency).
}

\strong{Phase along the chromosome}
\itemize{
\item Maternal phase per population is drawn by \code{generate_phase()} using
\code{phase_mode}:
\itemize{
\item \code{"all_coupling"}: all intervals coupling;
\item \code{"random"}: each interval is coupling with probability \code{1 - repulsion_rate}
and repulsion with probability \code{repulsion_rate};
\item \code{"vector"}: supplied \code{phase_vector} of length \code{T-1} with entries \code{0/1}.
}
\item Internally we maintain both a \verb{\{+1, -1\}} representation (\code{z}) and the
standard \verb{\{0,1\}} interval representation (\code{v}). We pass \verb{\{0,1\}} to the
C++ simulator by converting \code{z} to a per-marker flip vector.
}

\strong{Genotyping error}
\itemize{
\item Each offspring/marker call is independently replaced with a \emph{different}
genotype with probability \code{error_rate}. This matches the C++ core behavior.
}

\strong{Reproducibility}
\itemize{
\item If \code{seed} is provided, \code{set.seed(seed)} is called at the start. Note that
downstream C++ draws share R's RNG state via \code{RNGScope}, so the simulation
is fully reproducible under the same R and package versions.
